                  Firſt then, The Meaſure of Time ariſes from Minutes, 60 of them make an Hour, 24 Hours natural Day, &c. 7 Days goe to a Week. 4 Week to a Month, 13 ſuch Lunar Months, a Day, and Hours to a Year, though the Year is commonly divided into 12 Solar Months, or ſo many Signs,


which the Sun paſſes through, in the Circle of a Year; ſo that one Month carrys more days than another, as in this Antient obſerving Verſe is ſeen:



                        Thirty Days hath Fruit-bearing September;


                        Moiſt April, Hot June, and Cold November:


                        Short February Twenty Eight alone;



                        The other Months, have either Thirty One;



                        And February, when the Fourth Years Run,



                        Do's gain a Day from the ſwift moving Sun!


So that by this it is plain, that every fourth Year, called Biſſextile, or Leap-Year, there is allowed to February 29 Days.
